<h1>Current Situation: China</h1>
<br>
<h2>The Information Technology (IT) curriculum</h2>
<br>
<p>
Unlike the U.S., where each state or even each school district can have its own curriculum standard, China has a national curriculum standard, allowing only controlled degrees of regional variations. In high schools, the IT curriculum has a “1+5” structure: every student is required to take the course Foundations of Information Technology and choose one from the five electives, which are Application of Internet Technology, Application of Multimedia Technology, Introduction to Artificial Intelligence, Algorithm and Program Design, and Data Administration Technology.
</p>
<h2 class = "readMore" id = "readMore1">Read More &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp<img class="downArrow" src = '/images/arrows.png'/></h2>
<div class = "moreText" id = "text1">
<p>
However, there is a lot of criticism of the curriculum. Some of the major critiques are about the curriculum standard itself. First of all, the curriculum standard hasn’t been updated since 2003. When the curriculum was first developed, few families owned computers, so many students came to high schools knowing little about computers, and consequently the information technology curriculum assumed little background in computing. Yet over the last ten years circumstances changed tremendously: many students grew up immersed in technologies (known as “digital natives”), thus they have already acquired a lot of prior knowledge by the time they take the required course Foundations of Information Technology. Moreover, primary schools and middle schools began teaching information technology as well. In 2003, primary school and middle school’s IT curriculum standard wasn’t established, thus it was hard to establish a high school IT curriculum that connects and builds upon what were taught before high school <a href="/bib/?entry=li">(Li, Zhu & Dong 2003)</a>. Thus in a nationwide survey in 2013, many high school IT teachers estimated that Foundations of Information Technology has a lot of overlaps with the middle schools IT curriculum <a href="/bib/?entry=xiao2014">(Xiao, Guo, Fan & Huang 2014)</a>. Having to learn what they have already known, students may quickly lose interest in IT.
</p>
<p>
Meanwhile, many other criticisms are about how the curriculum standard is actually carried out by high schools. In short, the IT curriculum is a marginalized curriculum, and the graduation requirements play a large role in marginalizing it. Although the IT curriculum is part of the High School Graduation Examination, which determines whether students can get their high school diploma, it is not part of the National College Entrance Examination (NCEE), which determines whether and where students can go to college. The former is a lot easier compared to the latter, because students only need to pass the former in order to graduate, while they need to score as high as possible in the latter in order to be admitted by dream colleges. Thus, when schools have limited resources, they tend to pour the resources onto curriculums tested by the NCEE. Partly because the goal of the current IT curriculum is to enhance students’ information literacy—to make them qualified citizens of the information age, how well the students learnt the IT curriculum is not intended to be a college selection criteria, thus it can be hard to incorporate the IT curriculum into the NCEE, unless the curriculum standard updates and make tremendous changes. Indeed, the majority of the IT teachers surveyed did not eagerly wish the current IT curriculum to be incorporated into the NCEE <a href="/bib/?entry=xiao2014">(Xiao, Guo, Fan & Huang 2014)</a>.
</p>
<p>
Struggling with limited resources, many high schools cannot offer all five electives of the IT curriculum, leaving students with little or no choice. Moreover, the five electives are being offered highly unevenly. Application of Internet Technology and Application of Multimedia Technology are being offered the most. Compared to the other three electives, these two are easier because they are mainly focused on teaching students how to use the applications, while the other three require students to have some deeper understandings of the underlying theories <a href="/bib/?entry=xiao2014">(Xiao, Guo, Fan & Huang 2014)</a>. However, students have expressed considerable interests in the other three as well, although most of the time they do not have a chance to take these courses. Especially in the case of Introduction to Artificial Intelligence, a gap between student interest and actual enrollment clearly exists:
</p>
<p><img src="images/fiveElectives.png" alt="five electives data" id = "img1"/></p>
<p class = "caption"><a href="/bib/?entry=xiao2014">Student interest and actual enrollment in the five electives, actual enrollment estimated by the teachers (Data source: Xiao, Guo, Fan & Huang 2014)</a></p>
<p>
With limited resources high schools found it hard to recruit high quality IT teachers as well. Especially in the beginning years, many teachers did not major in computer science or related fields, but took up the role of IT teachers upon requests by schools <a href="/bib/?entry=zhu">(Zhu & Li 2005)</a>. Moreover, many IT teachers had limited understanding of information literacy, overlooking the humanistic value of information literacy and making the courses overly technical. By only teaching “whatever [technical skill] that is useful”, students’ emotional development, attitude formation, and thinking process were largely ignored <a href="/bib/?entry=liu">(Liu & Dong 2012)</a>. The High School Graduation Examination further worsens the problem. IT teachers had to prepare students for the exam, and the exam was mainly testing basic knowledge, concepts, and skills, hardly incorporating humanistic values of information literacy as described by the curriculum standard. Thus, the majority of the teachers (67%) thought that the High School Graduation Examination does not help to realize the goal of the IT curriculum <a href="/bib/?entry=xiao2014">(Xiao, Guo, Fan & Huang 2014)</a>.
</p>
<p>
Realizing these problems, the researchers have offered many suggestions to improve the IT curriculum, such as updating the curriculum standard to take students’ prior knowledge into consideration, developing assessment criteria that better reflect the curriculum’s goal, and recruiting/training high quality teachers, etc. <a href="/bib/?entry=liu">(Liu & Dong 2012;</a> <a href="/bib/?entry=xiao2014">Xiao, Guo, Fan & Huang 2014)</a>. While these are highly valuable suggestions, they may take a long time to implement, especially given that in the current Chinese education system, any change in the curriculum standard will affect the whole nation.
</p>
</div>
