<br>
<h2>Other Efforts</h2>
<br>
<p>
In addition to the IT curriculum, there are other notable efforts to foster high school CS education as well. The contemporary national standard of the math curriculum, updated in 2003, has taken the integrated curriculum approach: in a mandatory math course, there is a unit called “Introduction to Algorithms”, introducing flow charts, pseudo codes, simple BASIC commands, etc. The unit does not require the use of computers, and current math teachers teach the unit, thus the integrated curriculum utilizes existing resources well. Moreover, the unit is part of NCEE, although usually a relatively easy part <a href="/bib/?entry=xu">(Xu 2013)</a>.
</p>
<h2 class = "readMore" id = "readMore2">Read More &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp<img class="downArrow" src = '/images/arrows.png'/></h2>
<div class = "moreText" id = "text2">
<p>
There are efforts to integrate this unit with the IT elective Algorithm and Program Design, too, since both have a focus on algorithms. Some researchers think that both the math course and the IT course can benefit from the integration: for math, some math teachers are not very familiar with CS algorithms, and learning the material just on pen and paper can be boring. Yet due to high pressures to prepare students for the NCEE, math teachers usually do not have time to let the students actually program and test their algorithms on computers. For IT, as a marginalized curriculum, some students don’t take it very seriously, so it may use math, the “mainstream curriculum”, to elevate its status <a href="/bib/?entry=xu">(Xu 2013)</a>. In an experiment, students take these two courses at the same time, and program some exercises from the math course in IT class time. Results showed that both the student’s interest and grade improved in comparison to the control group, although it remains unclear whether the results are replicable <a href="/bib/?entry=xu">(Xu 2013)</a>.
</p>
<p>
<a href = "http://www.noi.cn" target="_blank">Chinese National Olympiad in Informatics (CNOI)</a> is another important effort. Organized by the <a href = "http://www.ccf.org.cn" target="_blank">Chinese Computer Federation (CCF)</a>, CNOI seeks “to popularize CS knowledge to teenagers in secondary schools, to provide motivation and a new way of thinking for the information technology curriculum, to provide opportunities for talented students to communicate with and learn from each other, and to cultivate and select CS talents.” <a href="/bib/?entry=ccf2016">(CCF 2016)</a> Unlike the IT curriculum which seeks to promote general information literacy, CNOI seeks to “cultivate and select CS talents”, thus it can be used as a selection criteria. For a long time it was closely linked to college admission: students who won top prizes got bonus points in NCEE—an exam in which every point could make a big difference, and the very top winners got guaranteed admission to good colleges.
</p>
<p>
Largely due to advantages in college admissions, CNOI attracts a lot of participants. In 2014, more than 60,000 middle and high school students participated in provincial level contests. However, the breakdown of the data showed that richer provinces generally had more participants and higher average scores <a href="/bib/?entry=ccf2014">(CCF 2014)</a>. Preparing students for CNOI requires a lot of resources, and usually only “key schools” in rich provinces can afford to prepare students adequately, hiring specialized teachers to train the students during weekends and holidays. Thus, it is doubtful whether CNOI attains part of its original goal of popularizing CS knowledge, because there are many barriers to participate, and students who participate may have high levels of interest in CS already. In this light, it is hard for CNOI to reach out to students who are less likely to receive quality CS education in high school.
</p>
<p>
Partly because of the realization that CNOI had strayed away from its original goals, in 2014 the link between CNOI and college admission was cut: students can no longer get bonus points in NCEE because of prizes won in CNOI. Notably, the same policy change was simultaneously made for all other national science Olympiads (chemistry, biology, physics, astronomy) as well. The policy change fits into the larger picture of the ongoing struggle between exam-oriented education and quality-oriented education: should the students devote more time to explore their interests and develop various aspects of their “quality”, rather than spending all their free time preparing for the largely exam-oriented CNOI?
</p>
<p>
Lastly, in recent years more and more high school students are choosing to study abroad in college. Instead of taking the NCEE, they look at foreign (mostly western) colleges’ admission criteria and try to prepare themselves accordingly. With new demands from these students, some private “international schools” and public schools in cooperation with private organizations began offering AP courses such as AP CS. While most students who study abroad are at least of the middle class, the number is growing fast. Moreover, the U.S. AP course system may provide a new way of thinking for Chinese education, for currently China does not have any large scale system that allow high school students to take college level courses.
</p>
</div>
