<h2>Going to Colleges</h2>
<br>
<p>
If they do not repeat a grade, students spend three years in high school. By the end of the first year, they are asked to choose between two tracks: the math and sciences track, or the humanities and social sciences track. Their choice will determine their following two years’ curriculum, leading up to different versions of the NCEE, and consequently, different college majors. While it is not impossible to change major in college, it can be very hard, and a lot of restrictions may apply. Although all students take the same courses prior to second year high school, a gender gap clearly exists: significantly more males choose the math and sciences track than females do, and consequently more males major in CS in college than females do. In 2015, 98% of “Computer Science and Technology” undergraduate majors chose the math and sciences track in high school, and only 33% of the major were female. Yet overall, it is a very popular major, having more than 100,000 graduates that year <a href="/bib/?entry=edepart2015">(The Education Department 2015)</a>.
</p>
