<h2>Reflecting History</h2>
<br>
<p class="previous"><a href="/history_chn">For more information on history, see History: China</a></p>
<p>
Overall, Chinese students’ access to high school CS education has gradually increased since the first movement started in 1984. The CNOI, founded in 1984, is accessible to only a few, and often more privileged, students. Yet the IT curriculum standard established in 2003 made IT education a requirement for every student across the nation. In the society, too, IT became more adopted, and “information culture” gradually shifted from “elite culture” to “popular culture.” <a href="/bib/?entry=zhu">(Zhu & Li 2005)</a> More and more families brought computers, to the extend that the IT curriculum standard became outdated because it assumes little computer background.
</p>
<h2 class = "readMore" id = "readMore3">Read More &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp<img class="downArrow" src = '/images/arrows.png'/></h2>
<div class = "moreText" id = "text3">
<p>
Yet the struggle between exam-oriented education and quality-oriented education has been present ever since the notion of quality-oriented education took center stage in the Outline in 1993. The CNOI is seen as mostly exam-oriented. Although the IT curriculum is articulated as part of quality-oriented education, it struggles with pressure from the long established tradition and the dominant school culture of exam-oriented education. Because schools see the NCEE as highly important and prioritize resources to prepare students for the NCEE, the IT curriculum has been constantly marginalized. Moreover, the IT curriculum itself can become exam-oriented too. The majority of IT teachers thought that assessment criteria in the High School Graduation Exam does not match with the goals described in the IT curriculum standard, yet when facing pressures to prepare students for the exam, many teachers looked at the assessment criteria rather than the curriculum standard to structure their courses <a href="/bib/?entry=xiao2014">(Xiao, Guo, Fan & Huang 2014)</a>.
</p>
</div>
